TEXT(beginproblem());

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
Suppose you want to solve the equation
\[f(x) = x^2-\cos x = 0\]
using Newton's method.  Newton's method starts with an initial approximation
\(x_0\) and then computes a sequence of approximations 
\(x_1\), \(x_2\), \(x_3\), \(\ldots\) via the formula
\[x_{k+1} = g(x_k), \quad k = 0,1,2,\ldots\]
where
\[g(x) = x - \frac{f(x)}{f'(x)}.\]

For the function defined above, 
\(g(x) = \)
\{&ans_rule(30)\}.  
$BR Letting \[x_0= 1\] you obtain
EOT

$ans="x-(x^2-cos(x))/(2x+sin(x))";
ANS(fun_cmp($ans));


$x=1/2;
$x=$x-($x**2-cos($x))/(2*$x+sin($x));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR \(x_1\) = \{&ans_rule(10)\},
EOT

ANS(num_cmp( $x));

$x=$x-($x**2-cos($x))/(2*$x+sin($x));
TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR \(x_2\) = \{&ans_rule(10)\}, and
EOT

ANS(num_cmp( $x));

$x=$x-($x**2-cos($x))/(2*$x+sin($x));

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR \(x_3\) = \{&ans_rule(10)\}.
EOT

ANS(num_cmp( $x));



